{
  "texts": [
    "These two elections are important, given that they were both highprofile polling failures, and both triggered comprehensive reviews of the polling system in each respective country: in the UK, Sturgis et al. (2016) produced a seminal report analyzing competing hypotheses to explain the polling failure; in the US, a similar paper was produced by Kennedy et al. (2018).",
    "The reports' conclusions are remarkably similar: i. little evidence for social-desirability bias ('Shy-Tory/ Trump' effects); ii.",
    "weak evidence for the role of incorrect turnout modeling; iii.",
    "some evidence for late-swing (stronger in the US than in the UK); iv.",
    "strong evidence for the effect of non-representativeness in the polls."
  ]
}